# Product Requirements Document
## My Advance Care Plan — Web App

**Version:** 1.3  
**Platform:** Web (desktop & mobile browser; responsive)  
**Future Platform:** Native iOS app (v2.0)  
**Audience:** Adults planning end-of-life care preferences; family/whānau assisting a loved one; healthcare professionals

---

## 1. Overview

### 1.1 Purpose
A responsive web app that digitises the "My Advance Care Plan" (Our Voice / Tō Tātou Reo) form, enabling users to create, store, update, and share their advance care preferences securely from any browser. Multiple people can manage their plans on a single shared device. The web app serves as the foundation for a future native iOS app.

### 1.2 Problem Statement
The current process relies on a paper-based 4-page form. This creates friction around storage, updates, sharing with healthcare providers, and accessibility in urgent medical situations. A digital solution removes these barriers while preserving the sensitivity and personal nature of the document.

### 1.3 Goals
- Allow multiple people to each maintain their own Advance Care Plan on a shared device
- Allow users to complete the full plan digitally, in their own time, from any device
- Enable easy updates at any point as wishes change
- Provide secure storage with optional sharing (PDF export, healthcare provider forwarding)
- Validate UX assumptions and gather user feedback before committing to a native iOS build

### 1.4 Web-First Rationale
Building a web app first allows the team to:
- Ship faster with a single codebase across all devices
- Gather real user feedback before investing in native development
- Avoid App Store review risk on a health-sensitive product
- Reuse form logic, data models, and PDF generation in the eventual iOS app

---

## 2. Target Users

| User | Description |
|---|---|
| **Primary** | Adults (50+) completing their own advance care plan |
| **Secondary** | Family/whānau assisting a loved one — may manage plans for multiple people on one device |
| **Tertiary** | Healthcare professionals (GPs, nurses, hospice staff) reviewing a plan |

---

## 3. Features & Requirements

### 3.1 Plan Selector (Home Screen)
The home screen is a plan list, not a single plan view. It allows one device to hold plans for multiple people.

- Lists all plans stored on the device, sorted by most recently updated
- Each plan card shows the person's name and last updated date with links to open or export
- **Create new plan** button — generates a new UUID-keyed plan and navigates to Personal Information
- **Import from backup** button — restores a plan from a previously exported `.json` file (always creates a new record with a fresh UUID)
- **Delete** action per plan card — requires inline confirmation before deleting
- Privacy notice: all plans are stored locally on this device; nothing is sent to any server unless an account is created
- Empty state: when no plans exist, shows a prompt to create the first plan or import a backup

---

### 3.2 Per-Plan Home Screen
Each plan has its own home screen at `/plans/[planId]`.

- Displays the plan owner's name (derived from Personal Information once filled)
- "← All plans" back link to the plan selector
- Circular progress ring showing 0–100% completion
- Section list with completion tick per section
- Last updated date and save status indicator (auto-save / unsaved changes / saving…)
- Backup (JSON export) button
- Sticky "Continue" bar pointing to the first incomplete section, or "Export Plan" when all sections are complete
- Disclaimer: plan will only be used if the person cannot communicate their wishes directly

---

### 3.3 Personal Information
Fields:
- Surname (required)
- First name(s) (required)
- NHI Number
- Date of Birth — calendar date picker (DD/MM/YYYY display; YYYY-MM-DD stored); month and year dropdowns for quick navigation; year range 1900 to current year
- Address (multi-line)
- Mobile (shown first)
- Home Phone

---

### 3.4 Enduring Power of Attorney
Supports multiple EPA attorneys, each assignable to one of two types:

**EPA types:**
- Personal Care and Welfare — makes decisions about health and daily life
- Property — manages finances and assets

**Per attorney, fields:**
- EPA Type (dropdown: Personal Care and Welfare / Property)
- First name(s), Last name
- Relationship
- Address (multi-line)
- Mobile (shown first), Home Phone
- Email

**Behaviour:**
- Attorneys are grouped on screen by type under two labelled sections
- Add/remove attorneys within each type independently; no fixed maximum
- Empty state shows quick-start buttons to add the first attorney of each type
- "Import from Contacts" button (coming soon — Contact Picker API on supported mobile browsers)

---

### 3.5 People to Include in Care Decisions
Up to 4 contacts, each with:
- First name, Last name
- Relationship
- Phone
- Email
- Add/remove contacts dynamically; minimum 1 shown

---

### 3.6 Will
- Toggle: Has the user made a Will? (Yes / No)
- If Yes: free-text field for where the Will is held

---

### 3.7 Personal Wishes
Three multi-line free-text fields:
1. **What is important to me** — hopes, fears, practical matters, spiritual care, family concerns
2. **What makes life meaningful to me** — values, people, pets, spiritual/emotional needs
3. **What I want my family and friends to know and remember**

Emotional support prompt displayed at top of section: acknowledges the section may be confronting, includes the Need to Talk? helpline (1737).

---

### 3.8 End-of-Life Preferences

**When I am dying, the following are important to me** (multi-select checkboxes):
- Keep me comfortable
- Take out tubes and lines that are not adding to my comfort
- Let my family and friends be with me
- Offer me something to eat and drink
- Stop medications that do not add to my comfort
- Attend to my spiritual needs
- Other (free-text)

**Place of death preference:**
- Toggle: Is the place I die important to me? (Yes / No)
- If Yes, single-select: At home (with address field) / In Hospice / In hospital / Other (free-text)

Emotional support prompt displayed at top of section.

---

### 3.9 Body Care & Funeral Wishes
- Burial preference: Buried / Cremated (radio buttons)
- Free-text: end-of-life ceremony or funeral wishes

---

### 3.10 Organ Donation
- Toggle: Willing to donate organs and/or tissues for transplantation? (Yes / No)
- Free-text: other comments
- Informational note linking to the NZ Organ Donation register (donor.health.nz)

---

### 3.11 Specific Treatment and Care Preferences
- Repeating two-column table: "I would / would not want" | "In these circumstances"
- Up to 10 rows; add/remove rows dynamically
- Label: *Please fill out with the help of your Doctor or Nurse*
- Emotional support prompt and doctor advisory displayed at top of section

---

### 3.12 Signature & Acknowledgement

**Legal status banner (non-dismissable):**
Displayed before the signature area. States that the digital plan is a record of preferences only and is not legally binding under NZ law. Instructs the user to print, sign by hand, and have it witnessed by a health professional for clinical use.

**User must acknowledge all 4 statements before signing:**
1. This is a record of preferences to guide the healthcare team.
2. It will only be used when the user cannot make decisions for themselves.
3. Medically futile/inappropriate treatments will not be administered even if expressed.
4. The record may be held electronically and shared with other health care providers.

**Signature capture — two modes, toggled by the user:**
- **Draw mode** — HTML Canvas; mouse, touch, or stylus; crosshair cursor; retina-safe via `devicePixelRatio` scaling
- **Type mode** — text input renders the typed name onto the canvas in italic serif font, scaled to fit; saves as a PNG data URL identically to a drawn signature

Signature date: calendar date picker (auto-populated with today's date).

**Witness (Health Professional) — completed on the printed PDF:**
- Fields captured in-app for record only (not a legally operative digital witness): First name(s), Last name, Designation, Email
- Date witnessed: calendar date picker
- Note explains that the witness section is completed on the printed PDF with a health professional present

**Completion prompt:** once all 4 acknowledgements are ticked and a signature is drawn/typed, a green banner appears with a direct "Export PDF" link.

---

### 3.13 PDF Export

**Export page features:**
- Plan completion summary with progress bar and clickable links to any incomplete sections
- Download PDF button — generates and triggers browser download
- Print button — generates PDF and opens browser print dialog via hidden iframe
- Save backup (.json) — exports plan as a JSON file for recovery
- "What to do next" checklist — 6 steps covering print, sign, witness, share, and review

**PDF generation (`pdf-lib`, client-side):**
- 4 pages mirroring the official form layout
- Red header bar with page number on every page; patient identity block repeated top-right on pages 2–4
- Noto Sans font (via `@fontsource/noto-sans`, served from `/public/fonts/`) for full Unicode support including Māori macron vowels (ā ē ī ō ū); `@pdf-lib/fontkit` required
- Helvetica (built-in) used for section headings to avoid OpenType ligature substitution issues (`fi`, `ll` etc.)
- Section headings auto-scale font size down if text is too wide for the heading band
- Page 1: cover + personal information
- Page 2: EPA attorneys (grouped by type, with email), care contacts (with email), will, personal wishes
- Page 3: end-of-life preferences (checkboxes), body care, organ donation
- Page 4: treatment preferences table + signature block (actual signature image embedded via `embedPng`) + witness fields
- Address fields correctly split on newline characters before rendering (pdf-lib ignores `\n` natively)
- Signature date formatted as DD/MM/YYYY in the PDF

---

### 3.14 Storage & Security

**Guest mode (no account) — current implementation:**
- All plans stored in `IndexedDB` (via `idb` library), keyed by UUID
- DB schema version 2 — supports multiple plans per device
- Data never leaves the device
- Warning displayed: data will be lost if browser storage is cleared
- JSON backup export/import available for recovery

**Multi-plan IndexedDB schema:**

| Store | Key | Value |
|---|---|---|
| `plans` | UUID string | `{ id, plan, savedAt }` |
| `history` | Auto-increment int | `{ id, planId, plan, savedAt, version }` indexed by `planId` |

- Each save bumps the plan version and snapshots to history
- Last 5 versions retained per plan; older versions trimmed automatically
- Schema migration handles plans saved under older schema versions (e.g. single-EPA object → `attorneys` array)

**Authenticated mode (future):**
- Account creation via email + password or passkey (WebAuthn)
- Data stored server-side, encrypted at rest (AES-256)
- HTTPS enforced; all API traffic TLS 1.3+
- Session management via secure, `HttpOnly` cookies

---

### 3.15 Updates & Versioning
- Users can edit any section at any time
- Each save creates a timestamped version history (last 5 versions retained per plan)
- Per-plan home screen shows date last updated
- Auto-save debounced at 1.5 seconds after any field change

---

### 3.16 Contacts Integration

**Applies to:** Section 3.4 (EPA) and Section 3.5 (Care Decision contacts)

#### Behaviour
- Each contact entry surfaces an **"Import from Contacts"** button alongside the manual fields
- Uses the browser-native Contact Picker API (`navigator.contacts.select()`)
- On selection, fields are auto-mapped:

| Contacts field | Form field |
|---|---|
| Given name | First name(s) |
| Family name | Last name |
| Address | Address (EPA only) |
| Phone labelled "mobile" | Mobile |
| Phone labelled "home" | Home phone |
| Phone labelled "work" | Daytime phone (EPA only) |
| First phone if no label match | Primary phone field |

- All imported values are editable after import — contact is copied, not linked
- Relationship and email fields are never auto-filled; must be entered manually

#### Browser Support & Fallback
- Contact Picker API supported on: Chrome for Android 80+, Safari iOS 16+
- On unsupported browsers: button is hidden; manual entry only
- Feature detection via `'contacts' in navigator && 'ContactsManager' in window`

#### Privacy
- Browser prompts for permission each time the picker is opened — no persistent access
- No contact data stored beyond what the user explicitly imports

#### Edge Cases
- Contact with no phone: import name/address only; phone fields left blank
- Contact with 3+ phones: inline disambiguation UI to assign numbers to correct fields
- Contact with no address (EPA): address fields left blank for manual entry

---

### 3.17 Date Pickers
All date fields use a consistent NZ-format calendar picker:

**Personal Information — Date of Birth:**
- Month dropdown (Jan–Dec) and year dropdown (1900 to current year) for quick navigation
- Day grid (Su–Sa) with correct first-day-of-week alignment
- Selected date highlighted in red; today outlined
- Stores as ISO `YYYY-MM-DD`; displays as `DD/MM/YYYY`
- Default view opens at current year minus 30 (practical for date of birth)

**Signature — Signature Date and Date Witnessed:**
- Same calendar UI as above but without year dropdown (dates near present)
- "Today" shortcut button
- Auto-populated with today's date on first open

---

### 3.18 Responsive Design & Accessibility
- Fully responsive: optimised for desktop (1024px+), tablet (768px), and mobile (375px+)
- Large tap targets (minimum 44×44px) for older users on mobile
- WCAG 2.1 AA compliance: keyboard navigable, sufficient colour contrast, screen reader support
- `<label>` elements correctly associated with all inputs
- Progress indicator showing completion status across all form sections
- Auto-save indicator in top navigation bar on every section page

---

## 4. Information Architecture

```
Web App
├── / — Plan Selector (home screen)
│   ├── Create new plan → /plans/[planId]/personal-info
│   └── Import backup (.json)
└── /plans/[planId]/
    ├── (index) — Per-plan home (progress, section list, continue bar)
    ├── personal-info
    ├── epa
    ├── care-contacts
    ├── will
    ├── personal-wishes
    ├── end-of-life
    ├── body-care
    ├── organ-donation
    ├── treatment-preferences
    ├── signature
    └── export
```

Each `/plans/[planId]/*` route is wrapped in a `PlanProvider` layout that loads and saves the correct plan by UUID.

---

## 5. Tech Stack

| Layer | Choice | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| **Framework** | Next.js (App Router) + TypeScript | File-based routing, layout nesting for per-plan context, easy Vercel deploy |
| **Styling** | Inline styles (no Tailwind) | Avoids class/style conflicts that caused rendering issues; full control |
| **Form state** | React Hook Form + Zod | Validation, schema sharing; `useFieldArray` for dynamic rows |
| **PDF generation** | `pdf-lib` + `@pdf-lib/fontkit` | Client-side; no server round-trip; works offline |
| **PDF fonts** | `@fontsource/noto-sans` (served from `/public/fonts/`) | Full Unicode incl. Māori macrons; avoids CDN/CORS issues |
| **Signature canvas** | Custom HTML Canvas component | Lightweight; supports Draw and Type modes; no extra dependency |
| **Storage** | `IndexedDB` via `idb` | Multi-plan; larger capacity than localStorage; structured data |
| **State management** | React Context (`PlanContext`) + `useReducer` | Plan load/save/auto-save; completion percentage; section status |
| **Backend (future)** | Next.js API routes | Single repo; easy server-side auth and sync |
| **Database (future)** | PostgreSQL | Relational; good for versioned plan history |
| **Auth (future)** | Auth.js (NextAuth) | Passkey + email/password |
| **Hosting** | Vercel or Fly.io (NZ/AU region) | HIPC data residency compliance |

---

## 6. Non-Functional Requirements

| Category | Requirement |
|---|---|
| **Accessibility** | WCAG 2.1 AA; keyboard navigable; screen reader tested |
| **Privacy** | Complies with NZ Privacy Act 2020 and Health Information Privacy Code 2020 (HIPC); no third-party analytics or ad SDKs; DPIA required before production data handling |
| **Data residency** | All PII (NHI numbers, health preferences, EPA details) must be stored on infrastructure physically located in New Zealand or Australia (acceptable under HIPC where NZ-region unavailable, subject to legal confirmation) |
| **Performance** | Lighthouse score ≥ 90; PDF generation < 3 seconds on mid-range device |
| **Browser Support** | Chrome 100+, Safari 15.4+, Firefox 100+, Edge 100+ |
| **Mobile Web** | Fully usable on iOS Safari and Android Chrome |
| **Offline** | Core form fully usable offline (IndexedDB; no network dependency) |
| **Localisation** | English (NZ) default; Māori (te reo) in v1.1 |
| **Security** | HTTPS only; OWASP Top 10 mitigations; no PII in URLs or query strings |

---

## 7. Out of Scope (v1.0 Web App)
- Native iOS / Android app
- Direct EHR / health system integration
- Server-side authentication and sync (currently guest/IndexedDB only)
- Māori language interface
- Real-time collaboration
- Account-based plan sharing between devices

---

## 8. Future: iOS App (v2.0)
Once the web app has validated the UX and gathered user feedback, the iOS app will be built with these advantages:

- Zod validation schemas inform the Swift data model
- PDF generation logic portable to Swift via `PDFKit`
- Native Contacts integration via `CNContactPickerViewController` (replaces Contact Picker API)
- Native signature capture via `PencilKit` (replaces HTML Canvas)
- Offline-first storage with Core Data (replacing IndexedDB)
- Face ID / Touch ID via `LocalAuthentication`
- iOS Lock Screen widget for emergency access to plan summary

---

## 9. Launch Prerequisites
The following must be completed before v1.0 ships:

1. **Legal** — obtain written legal advice on the standing of a digitally-signed advance care plan under NZ law (Protection of Personal and Property Rights Act 1988). The digital signature disclaimer banner wording must be reviewed and approved by a NZ health law practitioner.

2. **Privacy/Compliance** — complete a Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA) covering NHI number handling, health preference data, and HIPC 2020 Rules 5, 10, and 11. Confirm whether AU-region hosting satisfies HIPC or whether NZ-region is required. Provision infrastructure only after DPIA is complete.

3. **Clinical Safety** — submit crisis pathway content (helpline numbers, support panel wording, and contextual prompts on Personal Wishes, End-of-Life, and Treatment Preferences sections) for review and approval by a NZ clinical psychologist or palliative care specialist. Establish a quarterly process to verify helpline numbers remain current.

---

## 10. Success Metrics
- Plan completion rate (% of plans that reach the Signature screen)
- PDF export rate (% of completed plans exported)
- Plans per device (indicates family/whānau multi-person use)
- Monthly active devices retaining and updating plans
- Guest → account conversion rate (once auth is implemented)
- User satisfaction score (post-completion survey)

---

## 11. Open Questions
1. Should the app require a healthcare professional witness to countersign digitally, or is a downloaded+printed PDF acceptable for clinical use in NZ? *(Legal advice required — see Section 9)*
2. What is the legal standing of a digitally signed advance care plan in NZ? *(Legal advice required — see Section 9)*
3. Is NHI Number format validation (checksum) required?
4. Should the backend be hosted in NZ to satisfy data residency expectations for health data? *(HIPC compliance required — see Section 9)*
5. Should there be a PIN or device-lock option to prevent unauthorised access to plans on a shared device (e.g. family tablet)?
6. Should completed plans be shareable between devices without an account (e.g. via QR code or share link)?
